Recently I worked extensively with ACS as a part of the ZTVP project implementation.
Below are my 2 cents regarding the mentioned security concerns:

Regarding the Helm Chart usage in the operator, the ACS operator is a hybrid Go+Helm operator built on operator-framework/helm-operator-plugins.
This is documented in operator/ARCHITECTURE.md.
The Helm charts are embedded inside the operator binary at build time (from image/templates/helm/). They're not fetched from an external repository at runtime.
The operator doesn't run helm install. It uses the Helm library to render templates in-process and then applies the resulting Kubernetes manifests via the Kubernetes API.
It's true that ACS helm charts are not "certified" and stored in charts.openshift.io repository.
We should document this as a known exception in my opinion. 


Regarding the second concern, the Collector running with Root/Privileged permissions, it's a little bit more complicated.
The ACS Collector actually uses:
  securityContext:
    privileged: true
    readOnlyRootFilesystem: true
    capabilities:
      drop:
      - NET_RAW
(source: https://github.com/stackrox/stackrox/blob/master/image/templates/helm/stackrox-secured-cluster/templates/collector.yaml.htpl#L74-L79)
Additionally there is SCC binding to the privileged SCC.  

The eBPF program loading requires at minimum CAP_BPF (Linux 5.8+) or CAP_SYS_ADMIN (older kernels).
OCP 4.16+ runs RHEL 9.4+ with kernel 5.14+, so CAP_BPF is available, but eBPF tracing programs (kprobes, tracepoints — which collector uses to monitor process execution and network flows) additionally require CAP_PERFMON and CAP_SYS_PTRACE. The host /proc access requires CAP_SYS_PTRACE, and kernel module loading (legacy fallback when eBPF isn't available) requires CAP_SYS_MODULE. 

So, using `privileged: true` as a blanket covers all capabilities and all kernel versions.

Can it be improved? In my humble opinion there is room for research and improvement.
Theoretically with these granular capabilities, everything should work and be more secure.
  securityContext:
    privileged: false
    capabilities:
      add:
      - SYS_ADMIN      # or BPF on newer kernels
      - SYS_PTRACE     # /proc access
      - SYS_RESOURCE   # rlimit for BPF maps
      - PERFMON        # tracing programs
      - NET_ADMIN      # network flow monitoring
      - DAC_READ_SEARCH # host filesystem read
      drop:
      - ALL


Additionally, the compliance container in the Collector runs as `runAsUser: 0`.
This could potentially be separated into a non-root container with only DAC_READ_SEARCH capability for host filesystem scanning.
